				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \sum _{k=0}^{n-1} \frac{1}{(1-\zeta ^ka)^2}\,\zeta ^k =\frac{n^2a^{n-1}}{(1-a^n)^2} =\frac{n^2a^{n-1}}{\prod _{j=0}^{n-1}(1-\zeta ^ja)^2}. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}∑k=0n-11(1-ζka)2ζk=n2an-1(1-an)2=n2an-1∏j=0n-1(1-ζja)2.The latter sum on the left-hand side is the partial fraction decomposition of the right-hand side.

This shows in particular that the identity (3) holds for \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
